---
import { endpoints, modules } from "../content/docs";

const nav = ["Quickstart", "Connector", "API", "SDKs", "Modules", "Architecture", "Compliance"];
---

<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <meta charset="utf-8" />
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1" />
    <title>CDP-US Documentation</title>
    <meta
      name="description"
      content="Developer documentation for CDP-US: connector setup, API reference, SDKs, modules, and US compliance notes."
    />
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="/styles.css" />
  </head>
  <body>
    <header class="site-header">
      <a class="brand" href="/">CDP-US Docs</a>
      <nav aria-label="Documentation">
        {nav.map((item) => <a href={`#${item.toLowerCase()}`}>{item}</a>)}
      </nav>
    </header>
    <main>
      <section class="hero" id="quickstart">
        <p class="eyebrow">US B2B customer data platform</p>
        <h1>Start with one write key, then add modules.</h1>
        <p>
          CDP-US collects customer events and profiles first. Email, social intelligence,
          automation, consent, and billing modules consume that shared data foundation.
        </p>
        <ol class="steps">
          <li>Sign up and save the tenant id, API token, and write key.</li>
          <li>Install the browser connector or a server SDK.</li>
          <li>Enable modules once profiles and events are flowing.</li>
        </ol>
      </section>

      <section id="connector" class="section">
        <div>
          <p class="eyebrow">Install the connector</p>
          <h2>Browser and server ingestion</h2>
          <p>
            The browser SDK sends page and identify events. Server SDKs use the same
            <code>/v1/track</code> batch shape for backend events.
          </p>
        </div>
        <pre><code>{`import { createTracker } from "@cdp-us/sdk";

const cdp = createTracker({
  writeKey: "wk_...",
  endpoint: "https://api.example.com/v1/track"
});

cdp.track("Page Viewed", { path: location.pathname });`}</code></pre>
        <pre><code>{`import { CdpServer } from "@cdp-us/sdk-node";

const cdp = new CdpServer({ writeKey: "wk_..." });
await cdp.track("anon_1", "Order Created", { value: 49 });
await cdp.close();`}</code></pre>
        <pre><code>{`from cdp_us import CdpClient

with CdpClient("wk_...") as cdp:
    cdp.track("anon_1", "Order Created", {"value": 49})`}</code></pre>
      </section>

      <section id="api" class="section">
        <p class="eyebrow">API Reference</p>
        <h2>Versioned HTTP surface</h2>
        <div class="endpoint-grid">
          {
            endpoints.map((endpoint) => (
              <article class="endpoint-card">
                <div class="endpoint-title">
                  <strong>{endpoint.method}</strong>
                  <code>{endpoint.path}</code>
                  <span class={`status ${endpoint.status}`}>{endpoint.status}</span>
                </div>
                <p><b>Auth:</b> {endpoint.auth}</p>
                <pre><code>{endpoint.request}</code></pre>
                <pre><code>{endpoint.response}</code></pre>
              </article>
            ))
          }
        </div>
      </section>

      <section id="sdks" class="section two-col">
        <div>
          <p class="eyebrow">SDKs</p>
          <h2>Use the smallest client for each surface.</h2>
        </div>
        <ul class="feature-list">
          <li><b>Browser:</b> <code>@cdp-us/sdk</code> exposes <code>createTracker</code>.</li>
          <li><b>Node:</b> <code>@cdp-us/sdk-node</code> batches and retries server events.</li>
          <li><b>Python:</b> <code>cdp-us</code> provides <code>CdpClient</code> for backend jobs.</li>
          <li><b>Consent:</b> <code>@cdp-us/consent-sdk</code> gates analytics, email, sale/share, and TCPA messaging.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section id="modules" class="section">
        <p class="eyebrow">Modules</p>
        <h2>Upsells consume CDP data.</h2>
        <div class="module-grid">
          {modules.map(([key, description]) => <article><h3>{key}</h3><p>{description}</p></article>)}
        </div>
      </section>

      <section id="architecture" class="section two-col">
        <div>
          <p class="eyebrow">Architecture</p>
          <h2>CDP first, modules second.</h2>
        </div>
        <p>
          A tenant owns one US-region data foundation: write key, token, profiles,
          events, consent state, and enabled modules. The CDP collects and resolves data;
          modules read that data through product boundaries instead of owning separate identity stores.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="compliance" class="section two-col">
        <div>
          <p class="eyebrow">Compliance (US)</p>
          <h2>Controls that help teams meet obligations.</h2>
        </div>
        <p>
          CDP-US is designed for US-only deployments and includes consent surfaces for
          CCPA/CPRA, CAN-SPAM, and TCPA workflows. This documentation is not legal advice;
          customers should review their own policies and notices.
        </p>
      </section>
    </main>
  </body>
</html>
